<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-641-841  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 641 841.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Reseller News  Nov 12 1990 n394 p50(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The stock option paradox. (part 1)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hall, Steven E.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Start-up businesses in the computer and other high technologyindustries often raise money through employee stock options orother equity-based methods.andP;  Stock options also provide a way fornew, small businesses to compensate valuable employees before theycan afford to pay high salaries.andP;  They encourage imaginativeparticipation and high productivity by giving employees owners'interests in the business's performance.andP;  Vesting of stock optionsand ownership encourages employees to remain with the firm.andP;  Hightech firms sometimes run into trouble, however, because stockoptions are one of the less stable methods of raising capital andcompensating employees.andP;  Options may decline to an 'underwater'position and require unpopular repricing because of economicconditions beyond the control of the computer company or itsemployees.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     StockComputer IndustryStart-Up FinancingEmployeeInvestmentsFinancial Stability.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>